ular values through the experience of pain. Creatively exploring the analytic possibilities provided by the use of a camera, both text and film show how disruptive ritual techniques are used in healing to destabilise individual perceptions and experiences of agency, which allows patients to submit to the invisible powers of psychotropic medicine or God.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCinematography. 0aIslam. 0aJinnxQurʼanic teaching. 0aMotion pictures. 0aPsychiatry and religion. 0aPsychology and religion. 0aPsychosesxTreatmentxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aSpirit possessionxIslam. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh  aIslam.  aIslamic healing.  aanthropology.  aexorcism.  afilm.  aintercultural.  amental health.  apsychiatry.  apsychotropic medicine.  aritual healing.1 aSuhr, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614032640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526140326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526140326/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles